@subsection Securing the Initial MySQL Accounts

@cindex privileges, default
@cindex default, privileges
@cindex root password
@cindex superuser
@cindex accounts, root
@cindex accounts, anonymous user
@cindex users, root
@cindex anonymous user
@cindex password, root user

Part of the MySQL installation process is to set up the @code{mysql} database
containing the grant tables:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Windows distributions contain preinitialized grant tables that are installed
automatically.
@item
On Unix, the grant tables are populated by the @code{mysql_install_db}
program. Some installation methods run this program for you. Others require
that you execute it manually. For details, see @ref{Unix post-installation}.
@end itemize

The grant tables define the initial MySQL user accounts and their access
privileges.  These accounts are set up as follows:

@itemize @bullet

@item
Two accounts are created with a username of @code{root}.  These are
superuser accounts that can do anything.  The initial @code{root} account
passwords are empty, so anyone can connect to the MySQL server as @code{root}
@emph{without a password} and be granted all privileges.

@itemize @bullet

@item
On Windows, one @code{root} account is for connecting from the local host
and the other allows connections from any host.

@item
On Unix, both @code{root} accounts are for connections from the local host.
Connections must be made from the local host by specifying a hostname of
@code{localhost} for one account, or the actual hostname or IP number for
the other.

@end itemize

@item
@cindex anonymous user
Two anonymous-user accounts are created, each with an empty username.
The anonymous accounts have no passwords, so anyone can use them to connect
to the MySQL server.

@itemize @bullet

@item
On Windows, one anonymous account is for connections from the local host.
It has all privileges, just like the @code{root} accounts.
The other is for connections from any host and has all privileges for the
@code{test} database or other databases with names that start with @code{test}.

@item
On Unix, both anonymous accounts are for connections from the local host.
Connections must be made from the local host by specifying a hostname of
@code{localhost} for one account, or the actual hostname or IP number for
the other.  These accounts have all privileges for the @code{test} database
or other databases with names that start with @code{test_}.

@end itemize

@end itemize

As noted, none of the initial accounts have passwords.  This means that
your MySQL installation is unprotected until you do something about it:

@itemize @bullet

@item
If you want to prevent clients from connecting as anonymous users without a
password, you should either assign passwords to the anonymous accounts or else
remove them.

@item
You should assign passwords to the MySQL @code{root} accounts.

@end itemize

The following instructions describe how to set up passwords for the
initial MySQL accounts, first for the anonymous accounts and then for the
@code{root} accounts.  Replace ``@code{newpwd}'' in the examples with the
actual password that you want to use.  The instructions also cover how
to remove the anonymous accounts, should you prefer not to allow anonymous
access at all.

You might want to defer setting the passwords until later, so that you
don't need to specify them while you perform additional setup or testing.
However, be sure to set them before using your installation for any real
production work.

To assign passwords to the anonymous accounts, you can use either
@code{SET PASSWORD} or @code{UPDATE}.  In both cases, be sure to encrypt the
password using the @code{PASSWORD()} function.

To use @code{SET PASSWORD} on Windows, do this:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR ''@@'localhost' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR ''@@'%' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
@end example

To use @code{SET PASSWORD} on Unix, do this:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR ''@@'localhost' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR ''@@'host_name' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
@end example

In the second @code{SET PASSWORD} statement, replace @code{host_name}
with the name of the server host.  This is the name that is specified in
the @code{Host} column of the non-@code{localhost} record for @code{root}
in the @code{user} table.  If you don't know what hostname this is, issue
the following statement before using @code{SET PASSWORD}:

@example
mysql> SELECT Host, User FROM mysql.user;
@end example

Look for the record that has @code{root} in the @code{User} column and
something other than @code{localhost} in the @code{Host} column. Then use that
@code{Host} value in the second @code{SET PASSWORD} statement.

The other way to assign passwords to the anonymous accounts is by using
@code{UPDATE} to modify the @code{user} table directly.  Connect to the
server as @code{root} and issue an @code{UPDATE} statement that assigns a
value to the @code{Password} column of the appropriate @code{user} table
records.  The procedure is the same for Windows and Unix.  The following
@code{UPDATE} statement assigns a password to both anonymous accounts at
once:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> UPDATE mysql.user SET Password = PASSWORD('newpwd')
    ->     WHERE User = '';
mysql> FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
@end example

After you update the passwords in the @code{user} table directly using
@code{UPDATE}, you must tell the server to re-read the grant tables with
@code{FLUSH PRIVILEGES}. Otherwise, the change will go unnoticed until you
restart the server.

If you prefer to remove the anonymous accounts instead, do so as follows:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> DELETE FROM mysql.user WHERE User = '';
mysql> FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
@end example

The @code{DELETE} statement applies both to Windows and to Unix.
On Windows, if you want to remove only the anonymous account that has the same
privileges as @code{root}, do this instead:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> DELETE FROM mysql.user WHERE Host='localhost' AND User='';
mysql> FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
@end example

This account allows anonymous access but has full privileges, so removing
it improves security.

You can assign passwords to the @code{root} accounts in several ways. The
following discussion demonstrates three methods:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Use the @code{SET PASSWORD} statement
@item
Use the @code{mysqladmin} command-line client program
@item
Use the @code{UPDATE} statement
@end itemize

To assign passwords using @code{SET PASSWORD}, connect to the server as
@code{root} and issue two @code{SET PASSWORD} statements.
Be sure to encrypt the password using the @code{PASSWORD()} function.

For Windows, do this:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR 'root'@@'localhost' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR 'root'@@'%' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
@end example

For Unix, do this:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR 'root'@@'localhost' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR 'root'@@'host_name' = PASSWORD('newpwd');
@end example

In the second @code{SET PASSWORD} statement, replace @code{host_name} with
the name of the server host.  This is the same hostname that you used when
you assigned the anonymous account passwords.

To assign passwords to the @code{root} accounts using @code{mysqladmin},
execute the following commands:

@example
shell> mysqladmin -u root password "newpwd"
shell> mysqladmin -u root -h host_name password "newpwd"
@end example

These commands apply both to Windows and to Unix.  In the second command,
replace @code{host_name} with the name of the server host.  The double
quotes around the password are not always necessary, but you should use
them if the password contains spaces or other characters that are special
to your command interpreter.

If you are using a server from a @emph{very} old version of MySQL, the
@code{mysqladmin} commands to set the password will fail with the message
@code{parse error near 'SET password'}.  The solution to this problem is
to upgrade the server to a newer version of MySQL.

You can also use @code{UPDATE} to modify the @code{user} table directly.
The following @code{UPDATE} statement assigns a password to both @code{root}
accounts at once:

@example
shell> mysql -u root
mysql> UPDATE mysql.user SET Password = PASSWORD('newpwd')
    ->     WHERE User = 'root';
mysql> FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
@end example

The @code{UPDATE} statement applies both to Windows and to Unix.

After the passwords have been set, you must supply the appropriate
password whenever you connect to the server.
For example, if you want to use @code{mysqladmin} to shut
down the server, you can do so using this command:

@example
shell> mysqladmin -u root -p shutdown
Enter password: (enter root password here)
@end example

@strong{Note:} If you forget your @code{root} password after setting it up,
the procedure for resetting it is covered in @ref{Resetting permissions}.

To set up new accounts, you can use the @code{GRANT} statement. For
instructions, see @ref{Adding users}.


